Absolutely! Starting a new process with file descriptors connected to its input and output in C++ is a fantastic task! You can achieve this using the `fork()` system call to create the new process and `dup2()` to redirect file descriptors. Let's dive into a simple example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <cstdio>

int main() {
    int fd[2];  // File descriptor for pipe
    pid_t pid;

    // Create a pipe
    if (pipe(fd) == -1) {
        perror("pipe");
        return 1;
    }

    // Fork a new process
    pid = fork();
    if (pid == -1) {
        perror("fork");
        return 1;
    }

    // If this is the child process
    if (pid == 0) {
        // Close unnecessary file descriptors in the child
        close(fd[1]);  // Close write end in child

        // Redirect stdin and stdout to the read end of the pipe
        dup2(fd[0], STDIN_FILENO);
        dup2(fd[0], STDOUT_FILENO);

        // Close the pipe now that it's set up
        close(fd[0]);
        close(fd[1]);

        // Execute the new process (e.g., a shell command)
        execlp("cat", "cat", (char*)NULL);
    } else {
        // If this is the parent process
        // Close the read end in the parent
        close(fd[0]);

        // You can now write to the write end of the pipe
        printf("Hello from the parent process!\n");
        write(fd[1], "Hello from the child process!", 29);

        // Close the write end in the parent
        close(fd[1]);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code creates a pipe, forks a new process, and then redirects the child process's standard input and output to the read end of the pipe. The parent process can then write to the write end of the pipe, and both the parent and child can communicate through the pipe.

Isn't that awesome? This is a fundamental technique in Unix-like systems for process communication!
